  "text": "To assess motor function in mice overexpressing mutant ␣-synuclein in the substantia nigra with a second, independent assay, we monitored these mice on a forceplate actometer [CITATION_1] (Fig. 9A) . Quantitation of the movements of the mice on the forceplate revealed that WT ␣-synuclein overexpression significantly decreased the mobility of the mice as measured by the number of low-mobility bouts and spatial confinement (Fig. 9B) . Strikingly, the overall pattern of the effects of the mutations in ␣-synuclein on motor impairment was the same as that observed with the beamwalk assay, although the forceplate assay was notably noisier (Fig. 9) . Specifically, the PDassociated mutations, proline substitutions in the NAC region, and C-terminal truncations again enhanced the deleterious effect of overexpressed ␣-synuclein, whereas other mutations had no significant effect on the impairment of motor function by ␣-synuclein. The only difference between the results with the two assays (beamwalk and forceplate) was that the latter also identified a phenotype associated with one of proline substitutions (A19P), and suggested a trend for several other mutations.",
